TY  - JOUR
T1  - Moments of Truth: Examining Transient Authenticity and Identity in Service Encounters
AU  - Yagil, Dana
AU  - Medler-Liraz, Hana
Y1  - 2012/05/07
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2013/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2011.0252
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2011.0252
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 473
EP  - 497
VL  - 56
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We explore service employees' transient authenticity in their interactions with customers. Drawing on interviews with employees, we present a model of authenticity that begins with the salience of a customer's nonservice identity characteristics and an employee's identification with his or her task, both of which generate a sense of autonomy in employees. This psychological autonomy enhances the behavioral expression of authenticity, though such expression may yield costs involving loss of resources. Authenticity is reflected in uncalculated honesty, viewing a task as a personal endeavor, and conveying distinctive interpersonal closeness to customers.
AB  - We explore service employees' transient authenticity in their interactions with customers. Drawing on interviews with employees, we present a model of authenticity that begins with the salience of a customer's nonservice identity characteristics and an employee's identification with his or her task, both of which generate a sense of autonomy in employees. This psychological autonomy enhances the behavioral expression of authenticity, though such expression may yield costs involving loss of resources. Authenticity is reflected in uncalculated honesty, viewing a task as a personal endeavor, and conveying distinctive interpersonal closeness to customers.
